Real Banking Challenges (Important)

Below are the core problems every real banking / payment system must solve.

1️⃣ Data Consistency (No Money Loss)

Problem:
Money must never disappear or duplicate.

Example failure:

₹1000 debited

Credit failed

Money lost ❌

Solution used in banking:

ACID transactions

Strong consistency (CP)

Two-phase commit (in distributed)

Idempotency keys

Ledger / double-entry accounting

2️⃣ Concurrency (Double Spending Problem)

Problem:
Two transfers happen at same time from same account.

Balance = 1000
Thread 1 → transfer 800
Thread 2 → transfer 500


Final balance becomes negative ❌

Solutions:

Optimistic locking (version column)

Pessimistic locking (row lock)

Serializable isolation (rare, expensive)

Atomic DB operations

You will implement this soon.

3️⃣ High Availability (Bank must never go down)

Banking must run 24×7.

Challenges:

Server crash

DB crash

Network failure

Solutions:

Load balancer

Multi-region deployment

DB replication

Failover nodes

Health checks

Circuit breakers

4️⃣ Fault Tolerance (System survives failures)

If one service fails → whole system must not fail.

Example:
Notification service down → Transfer must still succeed.

Solution:

Async processing (Kafka)

Retry mechanism

Dead Letter Queue

Graceful degradation

5️⃣ Security (Very Critical)

Banking is top target for attacks.

Threats:

Fraud transfers

Data leaks

SQL injection

Unauthorized access

Solutions:

Encryption (TLS, AES)

OAuth2 / JWT auth

Role-based access (RBAC)

Audit logs

Fraud detection

Rate limiting

You will add security later.

6️⃣ Audit & Traceability (Every paisa tracked)

Bank must answer:

“Where did this ₹1 go?”

Solution:

Immutable transaction log

Ledger table

Event sourcing (advanced)

Full audit history

No delete, only append ✔

7️⃣ Scalability (Millions of users)

UPI handles 10,000+ TPS.

Challenges:

High concurrent transfers

Large DB size

Performance

Solutions:

Horizontal scaling

DB sharding

Read replicas

Caching (Redis)

Queue (Kafka)

8️⃣ Distributed Transactions

In microservices:

Account service → debit

Transaction service → record

Notification → send

If one fails → inconsistency.

Solutions:

Saga pattern (orchestration/choreography)

Outbox pattern

Idempotency

Event-driven architecture

(You will implement later)

9️⃣ Duplicate Requests (Network retries)

User clicks Transfer twice OR network retry happens.

Without protection → money debited twice ❌

Solution:

Idempotency key

Unique transaction constraint

Request deduplication

🔟 Performance vs Consistency Tradeoff

Banking chooses:

Consistency > Availability

Correctness > Speed

But must still keep response fast (<200ms).

